Relationship between transmission type and car performance in miles per gallon (MPG)

Nathalie Descusse-Brown

March 6, 2019

Overview

US automobile magazine Motor Trend has decided to look at the relationshop between car performance measured in miles per gallon (mpg) and the tranmission type for data extracted from the 1974 edition of the magazine. In particular, this paper seeks to address the following questions: 1. Is an automatic or manual transmission better for MPG? 2. What is the MPG difference between automatic and manual transmissions?

The data used for this analysis comprises fuel consumption and 10 aspects of automobile design and performance for 32 automobiles (1973-1974 models).

Data Processing and Exploratory Analysis

library(datasets)
data(mtcars)
mpg <- mtcars$mpg

for (i in 1:dim(mtcars)[1]) {
        if (mtcars$am[i]==1) {
                mtcars$trans[i] <- "manual"
        }
        else mtcars$trans[i] <- "automatic"
}

Model selection and results

We saw from the exploratory plot that there appears to be a large difference in miles per gallon performance between cars with manual and automatic transmission. Some investigation of the more meaningful covariables was performed with the use of nested tables and is reported in Appendix A. The covariable that were found to have a significant effect in our linear regression are weight, number of cylinders, 1/4 mile time, and gross horsepower.

library(MASS)
library(car)
lmregression <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt + I(factor(cyl)) + hp,data=mtcars)

summary(lmregression)

Permutations to increase sample size

We made the assumption of a normal distribution for the 2 selected subsets, automatic transmission and manual transmission. However because the number of samples is small, we used permutations to generate more samples.

group <- as.character(mtcars$trans)
testStat <- function(v,g) mean(v[g == "manual"]) - mean(v[g == "automatic"])
observedStat <- testStat(mtcars$mpg,group)
permutations <- sapply(1:100000,function(i) testStat(mtcars$mpg,sample(group)))
prob <- mean(permutations>observedStat)

head(permutations, 20)

Appendix A: Investigation of effect of inclusion of given covariable for model fitting

library(MASS)
library(car)
lmregression1 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)),data=mtcars)
lmregression11 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt,data=mtcars)

lmregression21 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt + I(factor(cyl)), data=mtcars)
lmregression22 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt + hp,data=mtcars)
lmregression23 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt + disp,data=mtcars)
lmregression24 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt + drat,data=mtcars)
lmregression25 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt + qsec,data=mtcars)
lmregression26 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt + I(factor(vs)),data=mtcars)
lmregression27 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt + I(factor(gear)),data=mtcars)
lmregression28 <- lm(mpg ~ I(factor(am)) + wt + I(factor(carb)),data=mtcars)

Based on the above comparison of effects of covariables, we selected am, wt, cyl and hp as the covariable for our model. Indeed, by adding these covariable one at a time we see that they are the only covariables shown by anova to have a significant effect.
